<TD WIDTH="9%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="font-family:ARIAL"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top"><FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:WINGDINGS">&#161;</FONT></SUP>&nbsp;</FONT></TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Under the EICP, when an individual&#146;s actions result in the filing of financial documents not in compliance with financial reporting requirements, the Company has the right to recoup or require repayment of an award
earned or accrued during the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">12-month</FONT> period following the first public issuance or filing with the SEC of the financial document not in compliance with such financial reporting requirement. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="toc348571_21"></A>The Role and Philosophy of the Compensation Committee </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee has primary responsibility for making compensation decisions for our NEOs other than our CEO. Our CEO&#146;s compensation is
approved by the independent members of the Board based on the recommendations of the Compensation Committee. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee operates under a
charter approved by the Board. The Compensation Committee uses information from Mercer&nbsp;(US)&nbsp;Inc. (&#147;Mercer&#148;), the Compensation Committee&#146;s independent executive compensation consultant, input from our CEO (except for matters
regarding his own pay) and assistance from our Human Resources Department to make decisions and to conduct its annual review of the Company&#146;s executive compensation program. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">44 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee works with a rolling agenda, with its heaviest workload occurring during the first
quarter of the year. During this quarter, decisions are made with respect to annual and long-term incentives earned based on the prior year&#146;s performance and target compensation levels are finalized for the current year. The Compensation
Committee also reviews and approves this Compensation Discussion&nbsp;&amp; Analysis. During the second and third quarters, the Compensation Committee reviews materials relating to peer group composition, tally sheets, competitive pay analysis and
other information that forms the foundation for future decisions. The Compensation Committee uses the third and fourth quarters to finalize decisions relating to the peer group and compensation plan design for use in the upcoming year. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee may, in its discretion, delegate all or a portion of its duties and responsibilities to a subcommittee of the Compensation Committee
and, pursuant to the provisions of the EICP, may appoint the CEO as a committee of the Board as necessary for the purpose of making equity grants under the EICP; provided, however, the Compensation Committee may not delegate the approval of certain
transactions to a subcommittee or to the CEO if such transactions involve the approval or grant of equity-based compensation to an &#147;officer&#148; for purposes of Rule <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">16b-3</FONT> under the Securities Exchange
Act of 1934 (&#147;Exchange Act&#148;) or a &#147;covered employee&#148; for purposes of Section 162(m) of the Internal Revenue Code (&#147;IRC&#148;) unless such subcommittee consists solely of members of the Compensation Committee who are (i) <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">&#147;Non-Employee</FONT> Directors&#148; for the purposes of Rule <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">16b-3</FONT> under the Exchange Act, and (ii) &#147;outside directors&#148; for the purposes of Section 162(m) of the IRC.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The philosophy of our executive compensation program is to provide a compelling, dynamic, market-based total compensation program tied to performance and
aligned with our stockholders&#146; interests. Our goal is to ensure the Company has the talent it needs to maintain sustained long-term performance for our stockholders, employees and communities. The guiding principles that help us achieve this
goal are: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>Recruit and retain. </B>Our program is designed to be market competitive and flexible to recruit and retain top talent for our critical roles. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>Pay for performance.</B> A significant portion of our executives&#146; compensation is tied to the performance of our Company, rewarding executives for both short-term and long-term progress towards our strategic and
operational goals. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>Aligned with strategy.</B> Our compensation program is aligned with the strategies of our Company. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>Aligned with stockholders.</B> Our compensation program, through both design and payouts, is aligned with the long-term interests of our stockholders. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>Reinforce robust succession planning.</B> Our compensation program plays a key role in making sure we have the talent we need for long-term success and to deliver our Company strategies. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"><B>Data-driven decision making.</B> We design our executive compensation program and make pay decisions considering a balance of information. </TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">45 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>Compensation Advisor Independence </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Under its engagement letter with the Compensation Committee, Mercer has acknowledged that the firm is retained by and performs its services for the
Compensation Committee while working with management to provide advice, counsel and recommendations that reinforce the Company&#146;s business strategy, economics, organization and management style. Mercer has provided and continues to provide
services and products to the Company in addition to its work for the Compensation Committee, including services related to global compensation consulting and surveys for various geographies. Mercer and its affiliates also provide products and
services to the Company that are unrelated to compensation, including expatriate consulting services (provided by Mercer), international benefits consulting and claims processing services (provided by Mercer) and coordination of certain third party
health and welfare benefits (coordinated by Marsh). Mercer&#146;s affiliates, Marsh USA Inc. and Marsh INSCO LLC, provided property and casualty insurance consulting services until June 2016. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee reviews all fees for services related to executive and director compensation provided by Mercer to the Compensation Committee, as
well as fees for compensation-related products and services provided to the Company. The decision to engage Mercer for other services was made by management. Neither the Compensation Committee nor the Board has a role in the engagement of Mercer or
Mercer affiliates that provide products or services to the Company that are unrelated to compensation; however, the Compensation Committee reviews the fees for such products and services concurrently with its review of compensation-related fees paid
to Mercer. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Fees paid to Mercer and its affiliates for services provided in 2016 related to executive and director compensation totaled $476,782. Fees paid
to Mercer and its affiliates for other services provided in 2016 were as follows: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="76%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">


<TR>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee also received and discussed with Mercer its letter to the Compensation Committee addressing factors
relevant under the Securities Exchange Commission (&#147;SEC&#148;) and New York Stock Exchange (&#147;NYSE&#148;) rules in assessing Mercer&#146;s independence from management and whether Mercer&#146;s work for the Compensation Committee has raised
any conflicts of interest, as well as Mercer&#146;s belief that no conflict of interest exists and that it serves as an independent advisor to the Compensation Committee. The factors addressed included the extent of any business or personal
relationships with any member of the Compensation Committee or any executive officer of the Company; Mercer&#146;s and its affiliates&#146; provision of other services to the Company; the level of fees received from the Company as a percentage of
total revenue of each of Mercer and Mercer&#146;s parent company; the policies and procedures employed by Mercer to avoid conflicts of interest; and any ownership of Company stock by individuals employed by Mercer to advise the Compensation
Committee. The Compensation Committee considered these factors before selecting or receiving advice from Mercer, and after considering these and other factors in their totality, the Compensation Committee identified no conflicts of interest with
respect to Mercer&#146;s advice. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In establishing compensation levels and awards for executive officers other than our CEO, the Compensation Committee
takes into consideration the recommendations of Mercer and the Human Resources Department, evaluations by our CEO of each officer&#146;s individual performance and Company performance. The Compensation Committee evaluates director compensation
primarily on the basis of peer group data used for benchmarking director compensation provided by Mercer. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">46 </P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Our executive compensation program includes the following key elements: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:9pt" ALIGN="center">

 COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Element</FONT></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:1pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt" align="left">&nbsp;</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #999999; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #999999">&nbsp;</TD>

<P STYLE="font-size:1pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt" align="left">&nbsp;</P></TD>

<P STYLE="font-size:1pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt" align="left">&nbsp;</P></TD>

 COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Key 2016 Actions</FONT></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:1pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt" align="left">&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:9pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b; padding-left:8pt"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:9pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Base Salary</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top">Fixed compensation component. Reviewed annually and adjusted as appropriate.</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top">Intended to attract and retain executives with proven skills and leadership abilities that will enable us to be successful.</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #3f000b; padding-right:2pt">Each NEO received an increase at the beginning of the year consistent with how the Company sets compensation as described
below.<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(1)</SUP></TD></TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#bfbfbf" STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:9pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b; padding-left:8pt"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:9pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Annual Incentive Award</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top">Variable, performance-based compensation component. Payable based on business results and individual performance.</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top">Intended to motivate and reward executives for successful execution of strategic priorities.</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #3f000b; padding-right:2pt">Targets as a percentage of base salary were established at the beginning of 2016 for each NEO.<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(1)</SUP> The metric weightings
were changed in 2016 as follows: Net Sales<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(2)</SUP> &#150; 50% to 45%, Adjusted Earnings per Share-Diluted<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(3)</SUP> &#150; remained at 40% and Operating
Cash Flow<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(4)</SUP> &#150; 10% to 15%.</TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:9pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b; padding-left:8pt"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:9pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Long-Term
Incentive Awards</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b">Variable, performance-based compensation component. Granted annually as a combination of Restricted Stock Units (&#147;RSUs&#148;), PSUs and stock options. The value of amounts actually earned
depend on Company and stock price performance.</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b">Intended to motivate and reward executives for long-term Company financial performance and enhanced long-term stockholder value by balancing compensation opportunity and risk, while
encouraging sustained performance and retention.</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b; padding-right:2pt">Targets as a percentage of base salary were established at the beginning of 2016 for each NEO. In 2016, the Compensation Committee approved
changing the equity mix from 50% stock options and 50% PSUs to 25% stock options, 50% PSUs and 25% RSUs. In addition, the Compensation Committee approved changing the PSU metrics and weightings for the 2016 &#150; 2018 performance cycle as described
in the section entitled &#147;Long-Term Incentives.&#148;</TD></TR>

&#147;Executive Summary.&#148; </TD></TR></TABLE>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The following charts illustrate the weighting of base salary, annual incentive awards and long-term incentive
awards at target for our CEO and our other NEOs during 2016: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="font-size:0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt" ALIGN="center">


<IMG SRC="g348571g78h48.jpg" ALT="LOGO">
 </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="toc348571_23"></A>Setting Compensation </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee&#146;s annual compensation review for 2016 included an analysis of data, comparing the Company&#146;s executive and director
compensation levels against a peer group of publicly-held consumer products companies. Mercer provides the Compensation Committee with advice, counsel and recommendations with respect to the composition of the peer group and competitive data used
for benchmarking our compensation program. The Compensation Committee uses this and other information provided by Mercer to reach an independent recommendation regarding compensation to be paid to our CEO, directors and other officers. The
Compensation Committee&#146;s final recommendation is then given to the independent directors of our Board for review and final approval. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Before 2015,
the Company had two separate peer groups, which we referred to as our Compensation Peer Group and our Financial Peer Group. Since 2015, the Compensation Committee has utilized one common peer group. Companies in the peer group used to benchmark
executive and director pay levels for 2016 (the &#147;2016 Peer Group&#148;) are: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="51%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="2%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="47%"></TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Brown-Forman Corporation</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">Hormel Foods Corporation</TD></TR>

<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">Kellogg Company</TD></TR>

<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>

<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">ConAgra Foods, Inc.</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">Mead Johnson Nutrition Company</TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Constellation Brands, Inc.</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">Molson Coors Brewing Company</TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Dean Foods Company</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">Mondelez International</TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Dr Pepper Snapple Group, Inc.</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">The Clorox Company</TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">General Mills, Inc.</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom">The J. M. Smucker Company</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">48 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee selected these companies after reviewing publicly-held companies offering
products/services similar to ours, with annual revenues within a range of approximately <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-half</FONT> to two and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-half</FONT> times our annual revenue (with the exception of
Mondelez International whom we also consider a peer company for executive talent) and market capitalization within a reasonable range of our market capitalization. The 2016 Peer Group was composed of companies with annual revenues ranging from
$3.6&nbsp;billion to $29.6&nbsp;billion (as of fiscal year 2015) and market capitalization ranging from $1.6&nbsp;billion to $71.3&nbsp;billion (as of December&nbsp;31, 2015). Hershey&#146;s fiscal year 2015 revenue of $7.4&nbsp;billion and
December&nbsp;31, 2015 market capitalization of $19.4&nbsp;billion were at the 51<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">st</SUP> and 56<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">th</SUP> percentiles, respectively. Except for
Colgate-Palmolive Company and Mead Johnson Nutrition Company, all of the companies in our 2016 Peer Group were included in our 2015 Peer Group. Kraft Foods Group, included in 2015, was not included in the 2016 Peer Group due to a merger occurring in
2015. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Data from the 2016 Peer Group was supplemented by composite data from consumer products companies ranging in size from $3&nbsp;billion to
$17&nbsp;billion in approximate annual sales. This information was included in three national surveys conducted by Aon Hewitt, Mercer and Towers Watson. The survey composite data provided us with broader, industry-specific information regarding pay
levels at consumer products companies for our NEOs. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee reviewed a report summarizing compensation levels at the 25<SUP
STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">th</SUP>, 50<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">th</SUP> and 75<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">th</SUP> percentiles of the 2016 Peer Group and the survey composite data for
positions comparable to those held by each of our NEOs. The Compensation Committee also reviewed a report comparing the target total cash compensation (base salary plus target annual incentive) and target total direct compensation (base salary plus
target annual incentive plus target long-term incentive) for each of the NEOs against these benchmarks. For retention and competitive considerations, the Company targets each NEO&#146;s total cash compensation and total direct compensation levels
around the 50<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">th</SUP> percentile of the 2016 Peer Group data or survey composite data applicable to his or her position. The Compensation Committee&#146;s final determinations with respect to base
salary, target annual incentive compensation and target long-term incentive compensation reflect consideration of the Company&#146;s and the NEO&#146;s performance, internal comparisons and other factors the Compensation Committee deems appropriate.
As a result of these factors, the target total cash compensation and target total direct compensation of our NEOs in 2016 was generally set around the applicable median. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">During 2016, the Compensation Committee received detailed tally sheets prepared by management. Each tally sheet captures comprehensive compensation, benefits
and stock ownership data. The tally sheets provide the Compensation Committee with a complete picture of each executive&#146;s current and projected compensation and the amount of each element of compensation or other benefit the executive would
receive in the event of voluntary or involuntary termination, retirement, disability, death, or upon change in control. The Compensation Committee considers this information, as well as the benchmark information, when making compensation decisions.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="toc348571_24"></A>Base Salary </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Base salary
is the largest fixed component of our executive compensation program and is determined by considering the relative importance of the position, the competitive marketplace and the individual&#146;s performance, responsibilities and experience. Salary
reviews are generally conducted annually at the beginning of the year. Each NEO&#146;s base salary is compared to internal and external references. Base salary adjustments, if any, are made after considering market references, Company performance
against financial goals and individual performance. CEO performance is evaluated by the Compensation Committee and independent members of the Board. The CEO evaluates the performance of his direct reports, including all NEOs, and reviews his
recommendations for salary adjustments with the Compensation Committee prior to its approval of the base salary for each NEO. If a NEO has responsibility for a particular business unit, the business unit&#146;s financial results also will be
strongly considered. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">49 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="toc348571_25"></A>Annual Incentives </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Our NEOs
are eligible to receive an annual cash incentive award under the One Hershey Incentive Program (&#147;OHIP&#148;), a program established under our EICP. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The OHIP links the NEO&#146;s payout opportunity to measures he or she can affect most directly. For 2016, our CEO and all employees reporting directly to him,
including the NEOs, had common financial objectives tied to total Company performance consistent with their responsibility to manage the entire Company. Total Company performance targets are established in the context of our announced expectations
for financial performance, prior year results and market conditions. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">For 2016, our NEOs were eligible to earn individual OHIP awards as follows: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Ms.&nbsp;Buck&#146;s target was initially set at 85% in January 2016. Upon her promotion to Executive Vice President, COO, Ms.&nbsp;Buck&#146;s target increased to 90%. The percent of target total direct compensation
for Ms.&nbsp;Buck is based on a base salary of $716,274, reflecting her target base salary both before and after the June increase. </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In
determining the target OHIP percentage for each of the NEOs, the Compensation Committee, and the independent directors in the case of our CEO, considered the value of target total cash compensation against market references. Target total cash
compensation levels for each of the NEOs fall within an appropriate range relative to the median for comparable positions given each incumbent&#146;s performance, responsibilities and tenure in the role. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">50 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In general, the final OHIP award is determined by multiplying the NEO&#146;s base salary, the applicable target
percentage and performance scores ranging from 0% to 200% based on Company and individual performance. The Company performance goals are established at the beginning of each year by the Compensation Committee. Individual performance goals also are
established at that time, or at the time of hire if later. If performance scores exceed the target objectives, a NEO may receive an OHIP payout greater than his or her target award value. If performance scores are below the target objectives, the
NEO&#146;s OHIP payout will be below his or her target award value, subject to no award if performance is below threshold levels. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">For 2016, Company
financial performance metrics accounted for 65% of each NEO&#146;s target award under the program. The remaining 35% was based upon individual performance toward achievement of up to six individual performance goals focused on strategic priorities
applicable to the NEO&#146;s position, but tied to the overall Company&#146;s top priorities for the year. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>2016 OHIP Performance Targets and Results
</I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Company performance targets for the 2016 OHIP were as follows: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Consolidated net sales<SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">(1)</SUP> of $7.571&nbsp;billion, a 2.5% increase from 2015; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">

<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

&#147;Executive Summary.&#148; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">We achieved below-target performance in net sales and operating cash flow and above-target performance in
adjusted earnings&nbsp;per&nbsp;share-diluted. As a result, 65% of the 2016 OHIP award for each NEO was based on the Company performance score of 107.09%. The remainder of the OHIP award was determined by individual performance ratings. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The individual performance goals for Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey centered on delivery of the Company&#146;s financial goals, strategic leadership and succession planning.
</P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">51 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">At the beginning of 2016, Ms.&nbsp;Buck served as our President, North America. On June&nbsp;2, 2016,
Ms.&nbsp;Buck took on an expanded role of Executive Vice President, COO, while continuing to lead the Company&#146;s <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">day-to-day</FONT></FONT> North American operations. Her goals and
evaluation reflected both roles. Ms.&nbsp;Buck was responsible for strategic leadership and delivery of the Company&#146;s financial objectives, establishing future growth pipelines, building critical capabilities and improving the Company&#146;s
operations. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Ms.&nbsp;Little, our CFO, had individual performance goals that included building the Company&#146;s global financial capabilities, delivering
continued process improvements and delivering on our strategic plan. The individual performance goals for Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day, Senior Vice President, Chief Supply Chain Officer, focused on delivering a supply chain network that enables growth and
delivering enterprise margin expansion. For Ms.&nbsp;Turner, Senior Vice President, General Counsel and Secretary, the individual performance goals included enhancing our global ethics and compliance culture as well as supporting our CEO and Board
on a variety of legal matters. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Following the close of 2016, the Compensation Committee provided the independent directors with an assessment of
Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s 2016 performance and achievement relative to his individual performance goals. Our financial results were around target despite challenging industry conditions in the category. Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey also delivered on his strategic
leadership goals, including enabling continued growth through portfolio expansion, investing in key geographies, capturing significant cost savings, delivering above-target innovation, succession planning and diversity efforts. Based upon those
assessments, the Compensation Committee recommended, and the Board approved, the individual performance award and total OHIP payout for Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey as shown in the table below. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey provided the Compensation Committee with his assessment of each NEO&#146;s 2016 performance and achievement in relation to their performance
goals. Based upon those assessments, Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey recommended, and the Compensation Committee approved, the individual performance awards and total OHIP payouts as shown in the table below. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Based upon a 65% weight for the Company financial score of 107.09% of target and a 35% weight for the individual performance award, our NEOs earned the
following 2016 OHIP awards: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="toc348571_26"></A>Long-Term Incentives </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">We provide long-term incentive opportunities to motivate, retain and reward our NEOs for their contributions to multi-year performance in achieving strategies
and improving long-term share value. In February of each year, the Compensation Committee awards long-term incentive grants to our NEOs. Prior to 2016, long-term incentive grants were comprised of PSUs and stock options. In 2016, we updated our
equity mix to include RSUs, increasing the retentive value of our long-term incentive program. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee, and the independent directors
in the case of our CEO, determines the value of long-term incentive awards made to each NEO by considering the NEO&#146;s target total direct compensation against internal and external references. The target award percentages approved in
February&nbsp;2016, expressed as a percentage of base salary, were: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="10%"></TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">The percent of target total direct compensation for Ms.&nbsp;Buck is based on a base salary of $716,274, reflecting her target base salary both before and after the June increase. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee values RSUs and PSUs using the closing stock price of the Company&#146;s Common Stock on the NYSE on the date of grant. The
Compensation Committee values stock options using the value of the stock options at the date of grant as determined for financial reporting purposes (the Black-Scholes value). Target total direct compensation levels for each of the NEOs fall within
an appropriate range relative to the median for comparable positions given the each incumbent&#146;s, performance, responsibilities and tenure in the role. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>Performance Stock Unit Targets and Results </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">PSUs are
granted to NEOs and other executives in a position to affect the Company&#146;s long-term results. At the start of each three-year cycle, a contingent target number of PSUs is established for each executive. This target is expressed as a percentage
of the executive&#146;s base salary and is determined as part of a total compensation package based on the peer group and survey composite benchmarks. The PSU award generally represents approximately <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-half</FONT>
of the recipient&#146;s long-term incentive compensation target award. Dividends are not paid on PSU awards during the three-year performance cycle. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><U>2014-2016 PSU Award </U></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The performance objectives for the
2014-2016 performance cycle awarded in 2014 were based upon the following metrics: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Three-year relative TSR versus the Financial Peer Group described below; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Three-year compound annual growth rate (&#147;CAGR&#148;) in organic net sales outside the United States and Canada; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">53 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">


<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top">Annual (as opposed to three-year) growth in adjusted earnings&nbsp;per&nbsp;share-diluted measured against an internal target for each year of the three-year performance cycle. </TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee selected these metrics to measure performance against internal targets aligned with our stockholders&#146; interests and investment
returns offered by our peer companies. Although the Company decided to utilize one common peer group beginning in 2015, PSU cycles prior to 2015 still utilize our Financial Peer Group. The Financial Peer Group is a high-performing group of companies
with whom we compete for investors in the food and beverage industry. Initially the Compensation Committee approved a Financial Peer Group of 15 companies with median revenues of $8.1&nbsp;billion. As a result of corporate transactions, Hillshire
Brands and Kraft Foods Group were removed from the Financial Peer Group. Therefore, 13 companies remained in the 2014-2016 cycle for use in assessing our Company&#146;s 2014-2016 TSR. </P>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee approves the annual adjusted earnings&nbsp;per&nbsp;share-diluted target for each year of the
three-year performance cycle at the beginning of the performance year. The annual component allows the Compensation Committee to establish performance thresholds, targets and maximums that reflect current business conditions, thus strengthening the
link between pay and performance for each year of the three-year cycle. Payment of any amounts earned, including amounts based on the annual performance goals, will be made in shares of our Common Stock at the conclusion of the three-year
performance cycle. The maximum award for any participant in a performance cycle is 250% of the contingent target award. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Targets and results for the
2014-2016 performance cycle and the Company&#146;s TSR and financial performance during the three-year cycle were as follows: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

(2)&nbsp;in the section entitled &#147;Executive Summary.&#148; </TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">At the conclusion of each three-year and annual performance period, the
Compensation Committee reviews the level of performance achieved and the percentage, if any, of the applicable portion of the target number of PSUs earned. In determining the final performance cycle score, negative adjustments may be made by the
Compensation Committee to the Company&#146;s performance score to take into account extraordinary or unusual items occurring during the period. No adjustments were made in determining the 20.66% performance score or the number of PSUs earned by our
NEOs for the 2014-2016 performance cycle. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><U>2015-2017 PSU Award </U></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The performance metrics and weightings for the 2015-2017 performance cycle are the same as the 2014-2016 performance cycle. In 2015, the Company decided to
utilize one common peer group for benchmarking compensation and for measuring financial performance in PSU cycles. The 2015 peer group originally included 15 companies, all of which were included in the Financial Peer Group used for the 2014-2016
PSU cycle, except that Hillshire Brands was removed as a result of a corporate transaction and was replaced by the Clorox Company. Kraft Foods Group was subsequently removed from the 2015 peer group as a result of a corporate transaction so that the
2015 peer group currently includes 14 companies. Actual Company results of $4.45 for the 2016 adjusted earnings per share-diluted metric reflected an 8% increase from 2015 exceeding the 2016 target of $4.37. As a result, 8.89% of the final award was
earned for this metric in the 2015-2017 performance cycle. These PSUs will be paid at the end of the three-year performance cycle to participating executives who are entitled to payouts under the terms of the program. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><U>2016-2018 PSU Award </U></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In December 2016, the Committee
approved changes to the performance metrics and weightings for the 2016-2018 performance cycle to simplify our program, reduce complexity and improve focus on our current long-term growth strategies. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The performance objectives for the 2016-2018 performance cycle are based upon the following metrics: </P>

 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">55 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>Stock Options </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Stock options are an important element of our long-term incentive program, enabling us to align the interests of NEOs with those of stockholders. In general,
stock options are awarded annually to the Company&#146;s executives as well as to other key managerial employees. Stock options entitle the holder to purchase a fixed number of shares of Common Stock at a set price during a specified period of time.
The right to exercise the options is subject to a vesting schedule. Because stock options vest over time and only have value if the price of our Common Stock increases, they encourage efforts to enhance long-term stockholder value. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee sets guidelines for the value of stock options to be awarded based on competitive compensation data. The stock option award
represents approximately <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-quarter</FONT> of the NEO&#146;s long-term incentive compensation target award. In 2016, the target number of stock options awarded to each NEO was determined by multiplying the
NEO&#146;s base salary by <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-quarter</FONT> of his or her target long-term incentive award percentage divided by the Black-Scholes value of each option on the grant date. The Black-Scholes option-pricing model is
described in Note&nbsp;10 to the Consolidated Financial Statements contained in the 2016 Annual Report on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> that accompanies this Proxy Statement. The actual number of options awarded may vary from the
target level based on each NEO&#146;s individual performance evaluation. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Stock options vest in equal increments over four years and have a <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-year</FONT> term. As required by the EICP, the options have an exercise price equal to the closing market price of the Common Stock on the NYSE on the date of the award. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">See Column&nbsp;(f) of the 2016 Summary Compensation Table, Columns&nbsp;(j) through (l)&nbsp;of the 2016 Grants of Plan-Based Awards Table, Columns&nbsp;(b)
through (f)&nbsp;of the Outstanding Equity Awards at 2016 Fiscal-Year End Table and Columns&nbsp;(b) and (c)&nbsp;of the 2016 Option Exercises and Stock Vested Table for more information on stock options awarded to the NEOs. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>Restricted Stock Units </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In 2016, we updated our long-term
incentive program to include RSUs in our annual equity mix. The Compensation Committee sets guidelines for the value of the annual RSUs to be awarded based on competitive compensation data. These RSU awards represent approximately <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-quarter</FONT> of the NEO&#146;s long-term incentive compensation target award. In 2016, the target number of RSUs awarded to each NEO was determined by multiplying the NEO&#146;s base salary by <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-quarter</FONT> of his or her target long-term incentive award percentage divided by the closing price of the Company&#146;s Common Stock on the NYSE on the grant date. The actual number of RSUs awarded may vary from
the target level based on each NEO&#146;s individual performance evaluation. Annual RSUs vest in equal increments over three years. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation
Committee also awards RSUs to NEOs and other executives from time to time as special incentives. RSUs also are awarded by the Compensation Committee to replace compensation forfeited by newly-hired executive officers and by the CEO to employees
other than executive officers from the RSU pool described below. In February 2016, retention RSUs were granted to Mmes. Little, Buck and Turner, which vest in the event the recipient remains employed by the Company and/or its subsidiaries as of the
third-anniversary of the grant date. In June 2016, retention RSUs were granted to Mr.&nbsp;O&#146;Day, which vest in the event the recipient remains employed by the Company and/or its subsidiaries as of the
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">one-year</FONT> anniversary of the grant date. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">See Column (e)&nbsp;of the 2016 Summary Compensation Table, Column
(i)&nbsp;of the 2016 Grants of Plan-Based Awards Table, Columns (g)&nbsp;and (h) of the Outstanding Equity Awards at 2016 Fiscal-Year End Table and Columns (d)&nbsp;and (e) of the 2016 Option Exercises and Stock Vested Table for more information
about RSUs awarded to the NEOs. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">56 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>Equity Pools </I></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">To ensure flexibility in providing awards for recruitment, retention, performance recognition or in conjunction with a promotion, the Compensation Committee is
authorized under the EICP to establish a stock option pool, a PSU pool, a RSU pool and a separate CEO discretionary equity pool for use by our CEO for such purposes. The pools are available for approximately 12 months from the date created. The
Compensation Committee determines whether to establish any or all of these pools annually. Options, PSUs and RSUs remaining in any pool at the end of the period do not carry over to pools established for a subsequent period. The CEO may not make
discretionary awards from any pool to the NEOs. Awards from the CEO pools and the CEO discretionary equity pool are made monthly according to an annually <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-determined</FONT> schedule. The exercise price for the
options is based on the closing price of our Common Stock on the date of the award. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="toc348571_27"></A>Perquisites </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Executive perquisites are kept to a minimal level relative to a NEO&#146;s total compensation and do not play a significant role in our executive compensation
program. The perquisites that we provide, include personal use of Company aircraft, security services for our CEO, and financial counseling and tax preparation reimbursement. See the footnotes to Column&nbsp;(i) of the 2016 Summary Compensation
Table for information regarding the perquisites received by our NEOs. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Our CEO and the other NEOs are eligible to participate in our Gift Matching Program
on the same basis as other employees, retirees or their spouses. Through the Gift Matching Program, we match contributions made to one or more <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-profit</FONT> organizations on a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">dollar-for-dollar</FONT></FONT> basis up to a maximum aggregate contribution of $5,000 per employee annually. These matching contributions are not considered compensation and are not included in Column&nbsp;(i) of the 2016
Summary Compensation Table. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="toc348571_28"></A>Retirement Plans </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">NEOs participate in our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> defined benefit pension plan (&#147;pension plan&#148;) and <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> defined contribution 401(k) plan (&#147;401(k) plan&#148;) on the same basis as other salaried employees of the Company. IRC regulations do not permit the Company to use base salary and other
compensation paid above certain limits to determine the benefits earned by the NEOs under <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> plans. The Company maintains a defined benefit Supplemental Executive Retirement Plan
(&#147;DB&nbsp;SERP&#148;), a defined contribution Supplemental Executive Retirement Plan (&#147;DC&nbsp;SERP&#148;) and a Deferred Compensation Plan to provide these and additional benefits that are comparable to those offered by our peers. Under
the provisions of the Deferred Compensation Plan, our NEOs may elect to defer payments from the DB&nbsp;SERP, DC&nbsp;SERP, OHIP, PSU and RSU awards, but not stock options or base salary. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The DB&nbsp;SERP was closed to new participants in 2006. No new participants have been or will be added to the DB&nbsp;SERP. NEOs and other senior executives
reporting to the CEO not eligible for the DB&nbsp;SERP are considered by the Compensation Committee for participation in the DC&nbsp;SERP. In comparison, the DC&nbsp;SERP typically yields a lower benefit than the DB&nbsp;SERP upon retirement. The
Company believes that the DB&nbsp;SERP, DC&nbsp;SERP and Deferred Compensation Plan help, in the aggregate, to attract and retain executive talent, as similar plans are often components of the executive compensation programs within our Peer Group.
The DC&nbsp;SERP was established as part of our Deferred Compensation Plan and is not a separate plan. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">See the 2016 Pension Benefits Table and
accompanying narrative and the 2016 <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Qualified</FONT> Deferred Compensation Table and accompanying narrative for more information regarding the DB&nbsp;SERP, DC&nbsp;SERP and other retirement benefits. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">57 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="toc348571_29"></A>Employment Agreements </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Company entered into an employment agreement with Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey in August 2012, which provided for Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s continued employment as
President and CEO and continued nomination as a member of the Board of Directors. In November 2015, the Company and Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey entered into an amendment to this employment agreement to reflect revisions to Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s compensation
and other benefits as a result of his election as Chairman of the Board. The employment agreement did not have a specified term. Under the terms of the employment agreement, in the event Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s employment was terminated by the
Company without Cause or he resigned for Good Reason (in each case as defined in the employment agreement), Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey would have been entitled to certain severance benefits. In the event of his termination after a change in control,
Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey would have been eligible to receive benefits under the Executive Benefits Protection Plan (Group 3A) (&#147;EBPP&nbsp;3A&#148;). He was not entitled to an excise tax <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">gross-up.</FONT> The employment
agreement subjected Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey to certain <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-solicitation</FONT> covenants under the ECRCA and to compensation recovery (clawback) to the extent
required by applicable law and regulations. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey retired as our President and CEO effective March&nbsp;1, 2017. In connection with his
retirement, the Company and Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey entered into a retirement agreement in February 2017 in order to set forth the benefits Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey will receive in connection with his retirement. The retirement agreement supersedes and replaces
Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s employment agreement. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In February 2017, the Company entered into an employment agreement with Ms.&nbsp;Buck to reflect the terms
and conditions of her employment as President and CEO, effective March&nbsp;1, 2017. The terms of Ms.&nbsp;Buck&#146;s employment agreement are substantially similar to the terms of Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey&#146;s employment agreement prior to the November
2015 amendment. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">See the section entitled &#147;Potential Payments upon Termination or Change in Control&#148; for information regarding the payments
Mr.&nbsp;Bilbrey and Ms.&nbsp;Buck would have received in the event of an applicable termination or change in control occurring on December&nbsp;31, 2016. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Other than as set forth above, we have not entered into employment agreements with any NEO. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="toc348571_30"></A>Severance and Change in Control Plans </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">All of the NEOs are covered by our EBPP 3A. The EBPP&nbsp;3A is intended to help us attract and retain executive talent and maintain a stable work environment
in the event of activity that could potentially result in a Change in Control. The severance protection provided under the EBPP&nbsp;3A upon a Change in Control is based upon a &#147;double trigger.&#148; The terms of the plan generally provide that
a covered NEO whose employment with the Company terminates in qualifying circumstances within two years after a Change in Control of the Company is entitled to certain severance payments and benefits. The EBPP&nbsp;3A also provides severance
benefits in the event of involuntary termination without Cause unrelated to a Change in Control or voluntary termination for Good Reason within two years after election of a new CEO. Change in Control, Cause and Good Reason are defined in the
EBPP&nbsp;3A. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">See the discussion in the section entitled &#147;Potential Payments upon Termination or Change in Control&#148; for information regarding
the payments that would be due to our NEOs under the EBPP 3A in the event of an applicable termination of employment or a Change in Control. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">58 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="toc348571_31"></A>Compensation Policies and Practices </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>Clawbacks </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Under the EICP, when an individual&#146;s
actions result in the filing of financial documents not in compliance with financial reporting requirements, the Company has the right to recoup or require repayment of an award earned or accrued during the twelve-month period following the first
public issuance or filing with the SEC of the financial document not in compliance with such financial reporting requirement. Repayment or clawback occurs where the material noncompliance results from misconduct, the participant&#146;s knowledge or
gross negligence in engaging in the misconduct or failing to prevent the misconduct, or if the participant is one of the individuals subject to automatic forfeiture under Section&nbsp;304 of the Sarbanes-Oxley Action of 2002. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">In 2008, the Company initiated the execution of the ECRCA by executive officers as a condition for the receipt of long-term incentive awards and, for new
executive officers, also as a condition of employment. The purpose of the ECRCA is to protect the Company and further align the interests of the executive officer with those of the Company. The terms of the ECRCA prohibit the executive from misusing
or disclosing the Company&#146;s confidential information, competing with the Company in specific categories for a period of 12 months following separation from employment, recruiting or soliciting the Company&#146;s employees, or disparaging the
Company&#146;s reputation in any way. For those officers or employees based outside the U.S., the restrictive covenants and terms may be modified to comply with local laws. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Failure to comply with the provisions of the ECRCA may result in cancellation of the unvested portion of PSU and RSU awards, cancellation of any unexercised
stock options and a requirement for repayment of amounts received from equity awards during the last year of employment, as well as any amounts received from the DB&nbsp;SERP or DC&nbsp;SERP. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><I>Tax Considerations </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:8pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The anticipated cost of the various
components of executive compensation is also a factor in the Compensation Committee&#146;s deliberations. Section&nbsp;162(m) of the IRC may limit the Company&#146;s ability to deduct certain compensation in excess of $1&nbsp;million paid to our CEO
or to our other NEOs who are employed on the last day of the fiscal year (other than officers who served as CFO during the year). This limitation does not apply to compensation that qualifies as &#147;performance-based&#148; under applicable
Internal Revenue Service (&#147;IRS&#148;) regulations or that is paid after termination of employment. The Compensation Committee has considered the effect of Section&nbsp;162(m) of the IRC on the Company&#146;s executive compensation program. The
Compensation Committee exercises discretion in setting base salaries, structuring incentive compensation awards and in determining payments in relation to levels of achievement of performance goals. The Compensation Committee believes that the total
compensation program for NEOs should be managed in accordance with the objectives outlined in the Company&#146;s compensation philosophy and in the best overall interests of the Company&#146;s stockholders. Accordingly, compensation paid by the
Company may not be deductible because such compensation exceeds the limitations, or does not meet the &#147;performance-based&#148; or other requirements, for deductibility under Section&nbsp;162(m) of the IRC. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC specifies certain rules and limitations regarding the operation of our Deferred Compensation Plan and other retirement programs.
Failure to comply with these rules could subject participants in those plans and programs to additional income tax and interest penalties. We believe our plans and programs comply with Section&nbsp;409A of the IRC. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">59 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="toc348571_32"></A>Stock Ownership Guidelines </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The Compensation Committee believes that requiring NEOs and other executive officers to hold significant amounts of our Common Stock strengthens their
alignment with the interest of our stockholders and promotes achievement of long-term business objectives. Our executive stock ownership policy has been in place for more than 20 years. The Compensation Committee reviews ownership requirements
annually to ensure they are aligned with external market comparisons. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Executives with stock ownership requirements have five years from their initial
election to their position to accumulate and hold the minimum number of shares required. For purposes of this requirement, &#147;shares&#148; include shares of our Common Stock that are owned by the executive, unvested time-based RSUs, PSUs earned
for the annual segments of open performance cycles and vested RSUs and PSUs that have been deferred by the executive as Common Stock units under our Deferred Compensation Plan. It is anticipated that executives will hold a significant number of the
shares earned from PSU and RSU awards and the exercise of stock options to satisfy their obligations. Minimum stockholding requirements for the CEO and the other NEOs are as follows: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="76%%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="66%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="6%"></TD>
<TD></TD></TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#3f000b" STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">

 COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Stock&nbsp;Ownership&nbsp;Level</FONT></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="font-size:1pt; margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt" align="left">&nbsp;</P></TD></TR>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #3f000b">4 times base salary</TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b; padding-left:8pt"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">CFO and Senior Vice Presidents</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #3f000b">3 times base salary</TD></TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#bfbfbf" STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:Times New Roman; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b; padding-left:8pt"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Other
executives subject to stockholding requirements</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #3f000b; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #3f000b">1 times base salary</TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The dollar value of shares which must be acquired and held equals a multiple of the individual executive&#146;s base salary.
Stockholding requirements are updated whenever a change in base salary occurs. Failure to reach the minimum within the five-year period results in a notification letter to the executive, with a copy to the CEO, and a requirement that future stock
option exercises and PSU payments be settled by retaining at least 50% of the shares of Common Stock received until the minimum ownership level is attained. The Compensation Committee receives an annual summary of each individual executive&#146;s
ownership status to monitor compliance. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center">60 </P>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:Times New Roman" ALIGN="center"><B><A NAME="toc348571_33"></A>COMPENSATION COMMITTEE REPORT </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B>To Our Stockholders: </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">We have reviewed and discussed with
management the Compensation Discussion&nbsp;&amp; Analysis. Based on that review and discussion, we have recommended to the Board of Directors that the Compensation Discussion&nbsp;&amp; Analysis be included in this Proxy Statement. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">Submitted by the Compensation and Executive Organization Committee of the Board of Directors: </P>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:Times New Roman"><B><A NAME="toc348571_34"></A>2016 Summary Compensation Table </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:Times New Roman">The following table and explanatory footnotes provide information regarding compensation earned by, held by, or paid to, individuals holding the positions of
Chief (Principal) Executive Officer and Chief (Principal) Financial Officer during 2016 and the three most highly compensated of our other executive officers, which collectively comprise our NEOs. The following table provides information with
respect to 2016, as well as 2015 and 2014 compensation where required. 2014 information is not provided for Mmes.&nbsp;Little and Turner because they were not NEOs in 2014. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
